reviews.review_text: PHIL !! I reacall being in the Phil Zone - and a whole contingent of Philipians on the floor where screaming WE WANT PHIL WE WANT PHIL...then he did Tom Thumbs Blues...yeahhhhhhh ...anyone else remember that?

Phil I remember that (heads yelling for Phil). You can actually hear some of it at the end of Big Railroad Blues. Great show. Really, a great run through MSG and then up at Boston Garden after that. My brother was at some of the Boston shows, and he still raves about 9/20 with the Help > Slip > Fire

Middle of a 9-day run
Three 3-day runs at MSG with a day off in between each. What a residency! By '91 the band was trying hard to meet demand for the NYC area. There was a lot of excitement for these shows but by the end it was not a run with the level of the MSGs just a year earlier (check the great 9/20/90 MSG). The previous show was made of sax, and gets most of the attention, but there are highlights scattered throughout the run. This one has a few of them for the cherry-pickers, salted into lots of just-below-average stretches. Complete-show buffs might save this for after other '91s (Boston, 6/9, Pine Knob, 4/28, 9/10, etc.). The 1st set is average with a couple sketchy parts and some stretches that just don't gel, but also has 91's possibly best Walkin Blues, with some great Bobby & Bruce. The 2nd set's Terrapin was inexplicably used for So Many Roads. It's good, but there are better ones from the era, and it fades before the jam into Drums. It follows one of 91's best Playing in the Bands, with a fine tranny into Terrapin (also cut from the box version). The set opener, Sugar Mag, is getting going when it's abruptly jerked by Jer into a pretty solid Foolish Heart in one of the weirdest '90s trannies. It sounds like they planned to do the transition while at the break but that the rest of the band weren't expecting it so soon?! This is also one of those fireworks, mind bending Drums that kept anyone from bathroom breaks and caused major hallucinations - feel the power of the spiral jelly universal distortion cruise ship. With Box of Rain you get a second Phil; one that's not too shabby. 1st set:  C- 2nd set: C Overall : 2¼ Stars Highlights: Walkin' Blues Playing in the Band>Terrapin>Drums SOURCES: Another super hansokolow matrix; it comes off just a bit more expansive than the SBD (except for some aud-distractions in Drums). Terrapin is on So Many Roads.
